<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18470510-1319">
               <interp inst="t18470510-1319" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470510"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470510-1319" type="date" value="18470510"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470510-1319-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1319-18470510 t18470510-1319-offence-1 t18470510-1319-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470510-1319-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1319-18470510 t18470510-1319-offence-1 t18470510-1319-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1319. <persName id="def1-1319-18470510" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1319-18470510" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1319-18470510" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1319-18470510" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES SMITH</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-1319-18470510" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1319-18470510" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1319-18470510" type="surname" value="ANDERSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1319-18470510" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE ANDERSON</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18470510-1319-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470510-1319-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470510-1319-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> stealing 1 iron shaft, value 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; and 1 iron wheel, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. the goods of <persName id="t18470510-name-1229" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1229" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1229" type="surname" value="KNEENE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1229" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470510-1319-offence-1 t18470510-name-1229"></join>Charles kneene</persName> and others—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, stating it to be 378lbs. weight of iron.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METACALF</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1230" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1230" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1230" type="surname" value="NICHOLLS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1230" type="given" value="BENJAMINE"></interp>BENJAMINE NICHOLLS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in partnership with Mr. Charles Keene and Christopher Nicholls—we have a manufactory in Granby-place, York-road, Lambeth—the way to it is through a pair of gates, through a passage, and then through another pair of gates to a yard, formerly in possession of Mr. Baker, which has been lately bought by the south-Western Railway Com<lb></lb>pany this piece of iron was a shaft—it is our property—I ordered it to be placed in that yard—it was taken out of the store, and left in the vacant ground about the 8th or 10th of April—I think I last saw it safe on Thurs<lb></lb>day afternoon, the 15th of April, and on the Monday following I missed that and a packing-case—in consequence of what I heard, I endeavoured to discover where the packing-case and shaft were gone—I went to the premises with an officer, from there to a field, and from thence to the back of a house, some distance off, where I found the packing-case—I saw the prisoner Anderson there—I asked him where the shaft was—he declared he did not know, neither had he seen it—I told him what shaft I meant, and asked him four or five times, and he constantly denied it—the officer, John Ould, was with me—I went the next day to Mr. Knowlden's, in Guildford-street, and the shaft was shown to me—I am quit sure it was mine—Anderson was afterwards brought to me in custody by Ould—Anderson said it was a bad job, he hoped I would let him go for that night, it was half-past nine o'clock, and he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184705100212"></xptr>
               <p>wished I would not give him into custody, as he said got important papers and keys which he wished to give up to Mr. Dalrymple, his employer—he said he would be there by nine o'clock in the morning—the shaft is worth 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 4<hi rend="italic">i.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know a person of the name of Ashlin? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I do not know that he was employed on those premises—I have heard so—Anderson admitted that the packing-case had✗ been removed by him, and gave a reason for removing it; but with reference✗ to the shaft, he said he had nothing to do with removing it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Ashlin is an engineer? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know—he is foreman of the Lambeth Water-works Company—the South-Western Railway Company got possession of these premised three or four weeks before that time—there had been nothing sold by auction on the pre<lb></lb>mises, but a great many things had been removed—there was no confsi✗ at all—this shaft was partly on the South-Western Railway premises and partly on our—no one could get it without the key to go us✗ that yard—we had one key—a man who had a stable there had a key, but he gave his key up, and a stone-mason, that had been in the yard three or four years, had one—I do not know Oakes, I have seen him, and he said he had command to remove those things that were on the premises of the✗ South-Western Railway.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALF</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were these things sufficiently on your premises to✗ indicate that they belonged to your warehouse? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; quite so—the shaft was leaning against the wall of our premises—anybody would has✗ assumed that it belonged to our warehouse—I went to the garden and was✗ Oakes there—Anderson afterwards admitted that he gave orders to Oakes to✗ remove it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1231" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1231" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1231" type="surname" value="ASHLIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1231" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH ASHLIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am foreman to the Lambeth Water-works Company. I have know the prisoner some time—I have known Anderson but a short time✗—On Friday, the 16th of April, I was working in Granby-place, taking up some water pipes, and Anderson came to me with some keys in his hand—he asked me if I would step a little way him—he took me to a gate which had a padlock on—he said on the way, that he wanted to point out to me where the thieves had been breaking in—he pointed to this piece of iron that as✗ there, and said, "They will have that before morning," and he asked if I knew in what way he could get it removed—I said, "I do not know, indeed"—he said, "Are you going to remain here all day"—I said, "Yes,"—he said, "Perhaps you will see some one who will move it"—in going back we met✗ Smith, and asked him if he would remove it—he said, "Yes," and Anderson gave him instructions to remove it—it was a round piece of iron—I did not take notice of it—we went together and Smith said, "Is this it?" Anderson said, "Yes"—Smith then said, "We had better have a drop of something to drink"—I did not see anything more of the iron—I afterwards saw Jones✗ and Parsons came running to their work—I asked them, where they had been—they said, to help a man with a piece of iron.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> While you were drinking, you men were running away with the piece of iron? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was some time after that I saw the me—I would not have sanctioned it—my men told me they gaw✗ it a lift—I was not at that time drinking in the public-house, I was with any✗ men—I was not in the public-house a minute—I do not know how Smith could say in truth that I gave him the iron to sell—what I have stated is the truth—I heard Smith say in the Police-court that I was the person who led</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184705100213"></xptr>
               <p>him to where the iron was—I was rather uneasy about this matter—I was 150 yards off—I was not there when the iron went away—after the state<lb></lb>ment were all given in I had a chat with Ould—I did not ask him to call at my house—I might have said, "Perhaps you will give me a call before you go to the Court"—I might have said that word to him—I will not say whether I did or not—I wanted to see him for a particular reason—because he made an omission in his statement before the Magistrate—I did not ask him to tell that on the second examination—he might do as he thought proper—he did not call at my house, to my knowledge—I never saw him there—he has been to my house with Anderson—he did not call after my observation to him—when I said he might give me a call, it was one evening in the York-road, by the Rising Sun—I did not hear that he had called after that—I do not know that he was treated at my house—I am not <hi rend="italic">know<lb></lb>ledgeable</hi> of his having anything to drink at my house—I have never heard it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was it the policeman omitted to say? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He omitted saying that Anderson said, "Ashlin, I am done for, for Gods sake intercede with the policeman to let me go until the morning"—I said, "You have been an officer, you know better than that; if this man gives you up, he is liable to lose his situation"—I did not want anything set right—I had no object at all—I am nor the prosecutor of this indictment—I am not supplying any of the funds—I do not know who is—I never had a key to this yard.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Anderson asked you if you could get him some one to remove this iron? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, that occurred in the yard where the shaft was—he had previously pointed out the shaft—I did not know exactly on whose premises it was—it might belong to the Railway Com<lb></lb>pany—my two men went to help in putting it on the truck—Anderson and I had a drop of gin together—I do not know what Smith had, it was something in a pot—my men are named Jones and Parsons—this happened about one o'clock in the day—Oake is porter to one of the auctioneers who had been selling the property—I was not aware whether Oakes had been helping the iron into the truck—I was not there—the public-house is about fifty yards from the yard—I think the gates were left open—there was not any one in the yard when we were in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1232" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1232" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1232" type="surname" value="MILBURY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1232" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MILBURY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in Mr. Nicholls' employ. I was in the stable in Mr. Baker's yard, which adjoins Mr. Nicholls' premises, on that day—I saw a shaft of iron in the yard—I saw five men go and take it out—they were Smith, Parsons, Jones, Oakes, and a boy—they brought it out, put it on the truck, and took it right away—Smith assisted in dragging the truck.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1233" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1233" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1233" type="surname" value="KNOWLDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1233" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KNOWLDEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my father, who is an engineer, in Great Guildford-street. On the 16th of April Smith came to me with some old iron, a piece of a shaft, and a rigger—he offered it for sale for 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a cwt.—I offered him 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., which he agreed to take—he took some old iron, and paid me the difference—I showed that shaft afterwards to Mr. Nicholls.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1234" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1234" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1234" type="surname" value="OULD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1234" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN OULD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 87.) I was called by Mr. Nicjolls—I went to a garden, and found a packing-case—Anderson was there—he deniced seeing the shaft—I saw the shaft at Knowlden's—I took Smith into custody—he made no reply at first, but he afterwards asked me who gave me infor<lb></lb>mation—I said I found it out by making inquiries—Milbury afterwards came, and identified him as the man he had seen with the truck and the shait✗—next day, on the way to the station, Smith said he bought it of a man whom he knew two years ago, but he could give nodesription of his name or address—on the 25th of April, I took Andreson—I said I wanted him re<lb></lb>specting an iron shaft—he said, "Ashlin is as deep in the mud, as I am in the mire"—I forgot myself at the examination before the Magistrate, but when we got to Ashlin's, Anderson said, "What a pretty mess you have brought me into, you have done this to screen yourself; you are as deep in the mad✗ as I am in the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184705100214"></xptr>
               <p>mire"—he said he thought it hard to be locked up, and not Ashlin—Ashlin said, "You know you have been a constable yourself, and if the constable gives you up, he may leave his situation"—after we left Mr. Ashlin, Anderson said he would <hi rend="italic">split</hi> about it to-morrow—I said, all we wanted was the truth—he asked me to go to Mr. Nicholls'—we called there, and he begged and prayed of Mr. Nicholls to let him go—he said he was a constable, he had got keys and papers to deliver up, and he would appear any time to-morrow that was necessary.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You did not happen to remem<lb></lb>ber some things on the first examination? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have not so good a head<lb></lb>piece as some people—I mentioned about his "slitting" the second time, not the first—I do not know whether Ashlin was uneasy about my forgetting it—he said I had mistaken it—I called at his house, but I did not see him—he was not at home—I saw a person, I do not know whether it was his wife or not—she acted like a domestic woman—I believe I had some ale—I did not pay for it—that was the day before I went to the Police-court, and then the next day I told about the "splitting," and about the mud and the mire.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Smith is a dealer in old iron? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He is a collector of it—he said at the station, after the charge was written down, "What, am I charged with stealing it?" <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALF</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How much ale had you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> One pint.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1235" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1235" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1235" type="surname" value="HODSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1235" type="given" value="HENRY BATEMAN"></interp>HENRY BATEMAN HODSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant surveyor to the London and South-Western Railway Company. they are extending their line from Nine✗ Elms—they have lately bought this yard, of Mr. Baker—Anderson was in the employ of the Company—he had authority to remove iron, or lead, or any stores belonging to the Company, to a place of safety, or into empty houses, where he could lock them up, and where they would be secure.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JOSEPH ASHLIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you go to an attorney's office for Smith, and instruct him to appear on his behalf? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I went to a solicitor on my own behalf.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did Anderson come to you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At past twelve o'clock in the day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JAMES MILLBURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did Smith come with the others to take these things? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think it was after dinner, a little after two o'clock—I did not see Anderson.</p>
               <p>
